  var ARTS=[
    {e:'🧠',t:'Why dopamine feels broken',sub:'5 min · the science',b:["Dopamine isn't the 'pleasure' chemical — it's the 'go get it' chemical. It spikes in anticipation of a reward, then drops once you have it.","Endless feeds hijack this. Every swipe is a tiny maybe-reward, so your brain keeps firing dopamine in anticipation, all day long.","Over time your baseline drops. Normal life — food, friends, a walk — stops registering, because your brain recalibrated to the firehose.","The fix isn't more willpower. It's lowering the flood so normal rewards feel good again. That's the whole reset.","Give it 7 days of less spiking and your receptors literally start recovering. The colour comes back."]},
    {e:'📵',t:'How to stop doomscrolling',sub:'4 min · practical',b:["Doomscrolling is an escape from a feeling, not a choice. The first move is to notice the feeling you're avoiding.","Add friction: log out, delete the app off your home screen, use grayscale mode. Every second of friction is a chance to choose differently.","Replace, don't just remove. Keep a 'instead' list ready — a book, a walk, a quick game here. The urge needs somewhere to go.","Use the 2-minute rule: when the urge hits, wait 2 minutes. Urges peak and fade fast. Usually it's gone.","Track wins, not failures. Every resisted scroll is a rep. Reps build the new default."]},
    {e:'🔁',t:'How habits change your brain',sub:'4 min · the loop',b:["Every habit is a loop: cue → routine → reward. Your phone buzzing (cue) → you check it (routine) → a hit of novelty (reward).","You can't easily delete a loop, but you can swap the routine. Keep the cue, change what you do, keep a reward.","Repetition wires it in. Each rep thickens the neural path until the new routine feels automatic.","This is why streaks matter — they're not vanity, they're physical wiring happening in real time.","Make the good habit obvious, easy and satisfying. Make the bad one invisible, hard and boring."]},
    {e:'🌅',t:'The morning routine that sets the day',sub:'3 min · routine',b:["The first hour programs your baseline. Start on a screen and you've already spiked and crashed before breakfast.","Win the first hour: no phone, water, light, movement. Even 10 minutes changes the entire day's chemistry.","Sunlight in your eyes early sets your body clock — which later sets your sleep, energy and mood.","Do one 'real' thing before you touch the internet. Make your bed, stretch, write a line. A small win first.","Keep it stupidly simple so you actually do it every day. Consistency beats the perfect routine."]},
    {e:'🌙',t:'The night routine for deep sleep',sub:'3 min · routine',b:["Sleep is where your brain cleans up and your dopamine system resets. Wreck it and everything else gets harder.","Screens at night are the worst offender: blue light delays sleep, and the content keeps your brain spiking.","Set a 'phone curfew' an hour before bed. Charge it across the room, not next to your pillow.","Wind down on purpose: dim lights, a few pages of a book, slow breathing. Tell your body it's safe to switch off.","Same sleep and wake time daily. A steady clock is worth more than any supplement."]},
    {e:'💪',t:'The confidence guide',sub:'4 min · identity',b:["Confidence isn't a feeling you wait for — it's evidence you build. Keep small promises to yourself and it grows.","Every time you do the hard thing you said you'd do, you cast a vote for 'I'm someone who follows through.'","Doomscrolling quietly destroys this. Each broken promise to 'just check for a sec' chips away at self-trust.","Start absurdly small. A promise you can't fail. Then keep it. Then make it slightly bigger.","Confidence is the by-product of a stack of kept promises. The reset is a 7-day stack."]},
    {e:'🎯',t:'Deep work: how to actually focus',sub:'5 min · focus',b:["Focus is the ability to hold one thing in mind without switching. Constant phone-checking trains the opposite.","Every switch costs you — it takes minutes to fully re-focus. Ten switches an hour and you never go deep.","Protect blocks: phone in another room, one tab, a timer. Start with 10 minutes and build.","Boredom is part of it. The urge to switch will scream. Don't obey it — that's the rep.","Deep work feels hard then quietly amazing. It's one of the few clean dopamine sources left."]},
    {e:'🏆',t:'How successful people focus',sub:'4 min · mindset',b:["High performers aren't more disciplined by birth — they design environments where the right thing is the easy thing.","They remove choices. Same routine, fewer decisions, less willpower spent on small stuff.","They protect their attention like money, because they know it's the real currency.","They use single-tasking. One thing, fully, then the next — not ten things half-done.","They rest on purpose. Recovery isn't lazy; it's what makes the focus possible."]},
    {e:'🌀',t:'How to stop overthinking',sub:'3 min · calm',b:["Overthinking is your brain trying to control the uncontrollable. It feels productive but it's just spinning.","Get it out of your head and onto paper. Written worries shrink; trapped ones grow.","Separate what you can control from what you can't. Act on the first list, release the second.","Set a 'worry window' — 10 minutes to think it through, then you're done for the day.","Action is the cure. The smallest step forward quiets the loop better than any amount of thinking."]},
    {e:'😴',t:'Why sleep matters more than you think',sub:'3 min · health',b:["Sleep isn't downtime — it's when your brain repairs, files memories and resets your reward system.","One bad night spikes cravings and tanks willpower the next day. You're not weak, you're under-slept.","Good sleep makes every other habit easier: better focus, calmer mood, fewer urges.","It's the highest-leverage thing you can fix. Nail sleep first and the rest follows.","Protect it like it's the foundation — because it is."]}
  ];
